{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 1. Introduction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds is a roleplaying rules engine suitable for play in any genre. Its abstract resolution methods and scalable character levels make it equally suitable to any genre, from epic fantasy to satirical soap opera.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.1 Version\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The first version of these rules Hero Wars was published in 2000 (ISBN 978-1-929052-01-1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The second version HeroQuest was published in 2003 (ISBN 978-1-929052-12-7). We refer to this as HeroQuest 1e to disambiguate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The third version HeroQuest: Core Rules was published in 2009 (ISBN 978-0-977785-32-2). We refer to this as HeroQuest 2e.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 HeroQuest Glorantha was published in 2015 (ISBN 978-1-943223-01-5). It is the version of the rules in HeroQuest 2e, presented for playing in Glorantha. We refer to this as HeroQuest 2.1e.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds was published as a System Reference Document (SRD) (this document) in 2018. The version of the rules here is slightly updated, mainly to clarify ambiguities, from the version presented in HeroQuest 2e and HeroQuest 2.1e. This makes this ruleset HeroQuest 2.2e, despite the name change. However, to simplify we identify this version as Questworlds 1e.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An Appendix lists changes in this version. As the SRD is updated we will continue to track version changes there.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.2 Core & Optional Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We flag some mechanics as Optional.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Questworlds engine is intended to be rules-lite, so we distinguish between the core mechanics, and optional ones. Previous presentations included all the rules and whilst they suggested some were optional in the text were less explicit in tagging those rules.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To make this SRD as flexible as possible we want to highlight which mechanics are optional; a rule in this section can easily be ommitted in any derived games presentation of the rules here. Lots of variations are possible, even on the core mechanics, whilst retaining the feel of Questworlds. These ones are highlighted as more detailed or complex options. They add depth to the game, but at the sacrifice of speed of play.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sub-headings under a heading should be considered part of the optional content.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If this is your first time reading these rules, you may wish to skip reading these sections marked on first reading and return to them once you understand the core mechanics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Optional mechanics can be brought in individually, they do not have to be all brought in together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.3 Why Questworlds?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds is meant to facilitate your creativity\u8212-and then to get out of your way. It is well suited to a collaborative, friendly group with a high degree of trust in each other\u8217's creativity. If the members of your group are often at odds and rely on their chosen rules kit as an arbiter between competing visions of how the game ought to develop, Questworlds is not the rules set you need. Stick with your more structured system of choice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.4 Numbering\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sections within this document are numbered. This does not imply that implementers need number them. Numbering however makes it easy to refer to rules in this document when page numbers may vary by presentation format for the purposes of error trapping or tracking changes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.5 Participants\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 1.5.1 Players\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each player creates a character or PC. The PCs pursue various goals in an imaginary world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 1.5.2 GM\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Games Master (GM), portrays the imaginary world in which the PCs live. The GM controls other people and creatures, or non-player characters, in this fictional environment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 2. Core Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stories consist of a series of obstacles, which the heroes must overcome in order to reach their final goal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player\u8217's encounter with a plot obstacle presents a conflict which must be resolved, either as a success or a failure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Whenever the characters try to overcome a difficult obstacle, the GM decides how difficult it will be. The player chooses an ability relevant to the conflict at hand, describes exactly what the PC is trying to accomplish, and how. The PCs success or failure, as determined by die rolls, changes the direction of the story, in either a big or small way.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.1 Abilities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Anything that a character can use to solve problems or overcome obstacles in a story can be an ability. The player decides how to describe abilities. Some abilities, such as a PC\u8217's central area of expertise, can be very broad, entailing a wide variety of related capabilities. Others might be very colorful and specific, granting a PC advantages when entering into a conflict with an opponent using a less directly applicable ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.1.2 Masteries\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworld abilities are scored on a range of 1\u8211-20, but are scalable. When you raise a rating of 20 by one point, it increases not to 21, but to 1M. The M signifies a game abstraction called a mastery. You have now reached a new order of excellence in that ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As you progress, you may gain multiple masteries. Multiple mastery is marked with a number to the right of the M symbol. If you have 10M2, you have two masteries. 10M3 means that you have three masteries, and so on.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In summary, to reflect abilities, or resistances, higher than 20, we divide the ability by 20, using a mastery for each multiple of 20 the ability is, and treating the remainder as the target number. So an ability of 27 translates into 1 remainder 7 or 7M; an ability of 43 translates into 2 remainder 3 or 3M2.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds genre packs may use symbols relevant to that genre to denote mastery, instead of M.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.2 Hero Points\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each character starts the game with a pool of 3 hero points, and gains more of them at the end of every session. These are a precious resource, as they are used both to boost characters\u8217' contest results, and to improve abilities over the long term.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.3 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player chooses an ability relevant to the conflict at hand, describes exactly what his character is trying to accomplish, and how. The GM may modify these suggested actions to better fit the fictional circumstances, and describes the actions of the characters or forces on the other side of the conflict.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If a PC enters a contest for which they have no relevant ability whatsoever, their base target number is a 6. Like ability ratings, it may be subject to modifiers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.1 Resolution Methods\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The core resolution methods are as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.1.1 Automatic Success\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The PC simply succeeds. This may indicate that failure would not be interesting (such as finding an important clue, and the PC has an ability that it is credible could help to uncover that clue), or that failure would make the PC appear to be incompetent at a trivial or simple task for someone with that skill (such as a hunter bringing in the evening meal in a forest filled with game animals).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Use Automaric Success when the PC has a relevant ability. If the PC has no relevant ability, they should find an alternate way to overcome the obstacle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.1.2 Simple Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player rolls a 20-sided die; the GM does the same.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GM compares the two results, and determines success or failure. Armed with this knowledge, they describes the outcome of the conflict, and any consequences to either participant.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If players enter into conflict with one another, each rolls dice, and the GM interprets the results, as usual.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.2 Framing the Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Contests in HeroQuest are more abstract than resolution methods in most other roleplaying games. They don\u8217't simply tell you how well a PC succeeded at a particular task: they tell you whether or not the PC achieved their goal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player(s) taking part in the contest and the GM start by clearly agreeing on 1) what prize is up for grabs and 2) what tactics they\u8217're using to try to get it. This process is called framing the contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Naming the prize: GMs start framing the contest by asking the involved player(s) what prize they\u8217're trying to win, or what goal they\u8217're hoping to achieve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? This may be a literal prize, like a gold cup, a gun, or a briefcase full of money.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? More often the prize is a metaphorical one, like access to a location\u8212-a treasure vault or the database servers containing the secret plans.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? In a struggle for resources, the winner gets control of something: a seat in government, a supply of goods, the assistance of an ally.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? In a fight, the prize may be the opponents themselves, who the PCs are fighting to capture or kill. Just as often they\u8217'll be seeking another goal and must incapacitate enemy combatants to get it. In this case, beating the enemy is the tactic, not the prize. For example the prize might be proof of the accused\u8217's innocence in a trial by combat, freeing a captive from the villain\u8217's lair, or intimidating a group into surrendering.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8226? The stakes may be defensive in nature, as when the PCs try to stop supporting characters from doing something harmful, like dropping a bomb on a city, or assassinating the king.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 2.3.2.1 No Repeat Attempts\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A contest represents all of a PCs attempts to overcome an obstacle. If a PC is defeated it means that no matter how many times they tried to solve the problem with their ability, the finally had to give up. THey can try again only if they apply a new ability to the task or the GM agrees that special circumstances exist.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.3.3 Resistance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The GM chooses a Resistance to represent the difficulty of the obstacle.\par}
