{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You get only one chance to receive an augment on any given contest. Failure does not allow other augment attempts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Augments can, however, combine with other modifiers, including those from benefits of victory and from plot augments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is impossible to augment an augment roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Augments last for the duration of a single contest, whether simple or extended.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.1 Quick Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Although some players like the uncertainty of rolling Game Masters may choose to run their game with calculated augments: divide the augmenting ability by 5 and round up.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 2.4.2 Plot Augments\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A plot augment is earned by overcoming a particular plot obstacle created by the Game Master. The magnitude of the plot augment is +3, +6, +9, or +M. The more challenging the plot obstacle, the higher the augment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.5 Armor and Weapons, Possessions and Equipment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Questworlds models arms and armor like it does everything else: any piece of gear, if sufficiently important to even mention, is treated as an ability the PC uses to solve problems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The degree to which a PC can overcome an obstacle with their armor and weapons depends not on any qualities inherent to the objects themselves, but to the points the player has allocated to the ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The difference between types of armor or weapons lies in the types of actions the player can describe, and what the PC can accomplish in unrelated actions and unusual contests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, Questworlds treats your possessions and equipment like it does everything else: as abilities you can use to solve problems, or to augment other abilities, which you then use to solve problems.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Having inappropriate equipment can result in an action being treated as a Stretch.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.6 Wealth\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In most settings, wealth is treated as just another ability you use to overcome obstacles. Your ability is not an objective measure of the size of your fortune, but instead indicates how well you solve problems with money and resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 3. Character Creation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.1 As-You-Go Method\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Concept The concept is a brief phrase, often just a couple of words, that tells the GM and other players what the PC does and how they act. When in doubt, start with a noun or phrase indicating the PC\u8217's profession or area of expertise, and modify it with an adjective suggesting a dominant personality trait:\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab haughty priestess\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab hotshot lawyer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab nai\u776?ve warrior\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab noble samurai\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab remorseful assassin\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab sardonic ex-mercenary\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab slothful vampire\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Now provide the character with a name.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab If the series uses other keywords, such as those for culture or religion, the PC may have them for free.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab When events in the story put the PC in a situation where the player wants them to do something, the player makes up an applicable ability on the spot. The first time the PC uses an ability (including the two the PC starts play with), assign an ability rating to it. This may be a breakout ability from a keyword. The PC is restricted to only one Sidekick.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab If the player wants, describe flaws.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Once the PC has 12 abilities (including the two for character concept), and up to three flaws the player is done creating their character.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.2 Assigning Ability Ratings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player has now defined a PC\u8217's abilities. These tell everyone what the PC can do. Now the player assigns numbers to each ability, called ratings, which determine how well they do these things.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The player assigns a starting rating of 17 to the ability they find most important or defining. Although most players consider it wisest to assign this rating to their area of expertise, which is also often a keyword, they don\u8217't have to do this. All other abilities start at a rating of 13.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Now the player may spend up to 20 points to boost any of the PC\u8217's various ability ratings, including keywords. Each point spent increases a rating by 1 point. The player can\u8217't spend more than 10 points on any one ability.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some genre packs may require PCs to have additional keywords that reflect the setting. These additional keywords come from the 12 ability allowance, so in many genres the PCs will have fewer wildcard abilities but better fit the setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Keywords\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player may build a character around one or more keywords. A keyword gives the PC a package deal: the PC gets a number of abilities by selecting a pre-existing character concept, which the player then modifies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Keywords are best suited for use as the character\u8217's core area of expertise.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In certain genres, characters may require multiple keywords: for example, one for area of expertise, another for species or culture, and perhaps a third for religious af liation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here are two ways to handle keywords. If in doubt, choose Umbrella.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as Packages}: Treat keywords simply as shorthand for a package of abilities. These can be boosted together during character creation, but are too unrelated to increase together during a game. Players are still free to use the keyword as an ability, and in fact may prefer to write only the specific abilities they\u8217've improved on their character sheet.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Keywords as an Umbrella}: Treat keywords both as raisable abilities and as a collection of more specific abilities. This approach keeps the character sheet from getting too cluttered but encourages specialization. Players write specialized abilities under the keyword, along with how much they\u8217've improved them:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In some settings, an ability may be listed in more than one of a character\u8217's keywords. Choose only one to detail it under.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 3.3 Flaws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A player may assign up to three flaws to their PC. Common flaws include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Personality traits:surly, petty, compulsive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Physical challenges:blindness, lameness, diabetes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Social hurdles: outcast, ill-mannered, hated by United supporters.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Flaws are assigned a rating equivalent to the PC\u8217's abilities. The first flaw is rated at the highest ability, the second shares the same rating as the second-highest ability, and the third equals the lowest ability. Certain keywords include flaws. Flaws gained through keywords do not count against the limit of three chosen flaws. All flaws after the third are given the same rating as the third ability. A player may designate flaws from keywords as their first or second-ranked flaw. When flaws manifest during play, the GM places the PC in a contest against them, rolls their associated ability ratings as Resistances to the PC\u8217's efforts. This method applies to flaws that primarily present the character with additional obstacles to overcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 GMs may decide during play that certain aws are better expressed as penalties to the PC\u8217's attempts to overcome other resistances. Divide the value by 5 and round (a flaw of 19 imposes a \u8211-4 penalty). This is appropriate where the player specifies that your ability to solve problems drops under certain specific conditions. Examples might include: * Tongue-tied in large gatherings. * Lousy with a stick shift. * Can\u8217't stand snakes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 5. Simple Contests\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.1 Simple Contest\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 5.1.1 Procedure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Frame the contest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Figure the PC\u8217's target number (TN) using the ability rating and any modifiers. The PCs TN is the rating of their ability, plus or minus modifiers the GM may give the PC.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab The GM determines the resistance. The GM opposes the PC with a resistance\u8212-the harder the task or tougher the opponent, the higher the resistance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Roll a d20 to determine the PCs degree of success or failure, then apply any bumps. The GM does the same for the resistance. Compare your rolled number with your TN to see how well you succeeded or failed with your ability. Remember to apply any bumps from masteries or hero points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Determine victory or defeat\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Optional: Determine Degrees of Success. Compare the PCs success or failure with the GM\u8217's on the Simple Contest Results table.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Optional: Determine Benefits of Victory or Consequences of Defeat.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Describe the result based on the agreed prize.\sa180\par}
